Creating images with R

with a little bit of magick

Tim Cross

March 13 2023

My meme

My meme is a spin on the whisper / hair rising meme, with the caption “Mum’s got the slow cooker on.” This is an original meme, as recently there have been a number of “memes” on social media platforms throwing off at slow cookers. I personally love my Mum’s slow cooker and decided to put a positive spin on it.

#Reading in magick package
library(magick)

#Loading in both the top half and bottom half of the image
tophalf <- image_read(path = "TopHalf.png")
bothalf <- image_read(path = "BottomHalf.png")

#Stacking both the top half and bottom of the image on top of each other
Meme <- image_append(c(tophalf, bothalf), stack = TRUE)

#Adding the text 
Meme2 <- image_blank(width = 1000, 
                          height = 1000, 
                          color = "#FFFFFF") %>%
  image_annotate(text = "Mum's got the slow cooker on",
                 color = "#000000",
                 size = 80,
                 font = "Impact",
                 gravity = "East",
                 location = "+800-100")

#Combining the text with my meme
Finalmeme <- image_append(c(Meme, Meme2))

image_write(Finalmeme, "Finalmeme.png")

My animated GIF

My gif is a countdown of 3, 2, 1 and then a photo of a quokka - a very cute Australian animal with the caption “smile”. With countdown-style gifs, often the images are inappropriate or offensive, this is certainly not one of those. This gif is designed to make people smile, even if you’re having a tough day.

#Reading in magick package
library(magick)

gif_image <- image_read(path = "Smile.png") %>%
  image_scale(500)


# creating a vector for the counts
counts <- 1 : 4 %>% as.character()

# creating each frame, where the text comes from the counts vector
frame1 <- image_blank(color = "white", width = 500, height = 500) %>%
  image_annotate(text = counts[3], size = 100, gravity = "center")

frame2 <- image_blank(color = "white", width = 500, height = 500) %>%
  image_annotate(text = counts[2], size = 100, gravity = "center")

frame3 <- image_blank(color = "white", width = 500, height = 500) %>%
  image_annotate(text = counts[1], size = 100, gravity = "center")

frame4 <- gif_image %>%
  image_annotate(text = "Smile", size = 100, gravity = "south")

# putting the frames in order using a vector
frames <- c(frame1, frame2, frame3, frame4)

# creating an animation
gif >- image_animate(frames, fps = 1)

#saving my images as a gif
image_write(image_an, "my_animation.gif")
